div.div: Where does VSCode store the enabled/disabled state for extensions?

Background A previous SO answer by @gino-mempin described how to query the SQLite tables in the state.vscdb files that contain the extension states using the SQLite browser. To query the vscdb programmatically using PowerShell, see the instructions below. My other SO answer about querying for cookies also explores this further. Paths to settings store(s) Recall that the global settings.json file location by operating system is
Operating System Global Settings Path
Windows %APPDATA%\Code\User\settings.json or $env:APPDATA\Code\User\settings.json macOS $HOME/Library/Application\ Support/Code/User/settings.json Linux $HOME/.config/Code/User/settings.json Resolve state.vscdb path For state.vscdb sqlite settings store, relative to settings.json , state.vscdb is located in ./User/globalStorage/state.vscdb . I use an asterisk * after Code to account for possible the Code - Insiders construction of the Insiders build, if you're on the Insiders channel. Resolve-Path "$env:APPDATA\Code*\User\globalStorage\state.vscdb" # global settings store for extensions * ls $HOME/Library/Application\ Support/Code*/User/settings.json * ls $HOME/.config/Code*/User/settings.json Workspace settings at workspaceStorage For workspace specific settings, again relative to the settings.json , state.vscdb per workspace is stored in ./User/workspaceStorage//state.vscdb Again, for example, PowerShell in Windows: Resolve-Path "$env:APPDATA\Code*\User\workspaceStorage\*\state.vscdb" # workspace settings store for extensions * ls $HOME/Library/Application\ Support/Code*/User/workspaceStorage/*/state.vscdb * ls $HOME/.config/Code*/User/workspaceStorage/*/state.vscdb Specific workspace settings The ExtensionContext.storageUri refers to the URI of a workspace specific directory in which the extension can store a private state. This can be found using the Developer Tools (Help > Toggle Developer Tools)
Then, in the console, type let config = await vscode.context.resolveConfiguration(); config.workspace; Here is a screen recording of this process:
See the VS Code API docs for more information on the ExtensionContext.storageUri within the context of extension development. Querying vscdb settings store Windows PowerShell Here is a simple example of how we can query the vscdb (this example loops through all the workspaces) using @jeffery-hicks's mySQLite in PowerShell: <# Prepare a convenience class to store our query results #> # Not strictly necessary, but it simplifies the query loop (27 more lines were trimmed) These are the results:
Command Result
`$workspaceSettings Format-Table -AutoSize -Wrap`
`$workspaceSettings[$settings.Workspace] Format-Table -AutoSize -Wrap`
If you want to convert the settings into a string, you can use the PowerShell: [System.Text.Encoding]::Default.GetString($workspaceSettings[$settings.Workspace].ItemTable['history.entries']) # Change 'history.entries' to the key of the settings you want to check *nix-like systems with bash For Linux and macOS, here’s the equivalent bash script using xxd and the sqlite3 command-line tool*: #!/bin/bash

Please note that xxd is a part of the vim package, so you’ll need to have vim installed on your system for this to work. * This script will not run as-is, since there is no universal (cross-platform) solution for glob expansion in bash. Loading the Word assemblies is actually a two-step process in PowerShell Core:
First, add the base assemblies into the pwsh environment; then, Add the target interop assembly.
Thanks to @Patrick Meinecke for clarifying this on GitHub. # First load MS Office base assemblies into the environment Add-Type -Path $env:WINDIR\assembly\GAC_MSIL\office\*\office.dll -PassThru # Use -PassThru to verify it worked (otherwise, fails silently) (4 more lines were trimmed) Then, you can automate the Word application for your own needs. For example, convert all txt files into docx (uses Get-ShortName from PoshFunctions): #Requires -Modules PoshFunctions $wordApp = New-Object -ComObject Word.Application (25 more lines were trimmed) I tested this on my machine and it was able to convert all txt into docx . These are syntheses of techniques provided within Justin Loring's ConvertTo-OSCWord and Steve Knutson's blog post converting word document format with powershell; although both of those are incomplete and only used as guides.
Unable to switch app language/locale at runtime in a .NET MAUI Blazor Hybrid Application

I'm currently developing a .NET MAUI Blazor hybrid application (GitHub repo here) and I've encountered an issue with changing the locale at runtime.
Component Version
.NET SDK 8.0.200-preview.23624.5
IDE Microsoft Visual Studio Community 2022 (64-bit) - Preview
Version 17.9.0 Preview 4.0
My application aims (but fails) to support multiple languages, and I want users to be able to switch between these languages at runtime in the Settings page. However, no matter what approach I try, the result is always the same: The application receives the language request, but the app culture never changes. My debug output always shows: OnSubmitLanguage: fr # This is the language I chose Current Culture: en-CA # This is my computer's locale (3 more lines were trimmed) To achieve this, I've tried several approaches:
Traditional AppRes Approach: Initially, I tried using the traditional AppRes approach for localization. However, this did not allow me to change the locale at runtime. Although I choose to switch languages, the app culture (and hence, language) never changes:
Settings page Language Selector Settings page Save Button Result in the debug window Localizer Approach: Next, I tried using the newer IStringLocalizer service, which is recommended for localization in .NET 6 and onwards. Despite setting the culture as shown below, the UI did not update to reflect the new culture. public void OnSubmitLanguage(EventArgs args) { (8 more lines were trimmed) Multilingual App Toolkit Approach: I also tried using the Multilingual App Toolkit, which is a contemporary recommendation for localization in .NET applications. However, this approach also did not result in the desired behavior.
Cookie Setting Approach: Finally, I tried storing the selected culture in a cookie. For this, I created a CookieService class and used it to set the culture cookie. However, this also did not result in the UI updating to the new culture. public void OnSubmitLanguage(EventArgs args) { (11 more lines were trimmed) Despite trying these different approaches, I'm still unable to change the locale at runtime. The CurrentCulture and CurrentUICulture remain unchanged after the method is called, as indicated by the debug prints. Has anyone encountered a similar issue or does anyone have any suggestions on what I might be doing wrong? Any help would be greatly appreciated!
How to write C# constructor with inner exception param

I'm trying to create a custom exception class in C# 12.0 (.NET 8.0, SDK Version: 8.0.100-rc.2.23502.2) that supports a constructor with an inner exception parameter. Here's the code I initially tried: public class TokenAcquisitionException(string message) : Exception(message) { (10 more lines were trimmed) However, when I try to compile this code, I get the following error: Error CS8862 A constructor declared in a type with parameter list must have 'this' constructor initializer. I found a GitHub issue that discusses a similar error, but it's related to records in C# 9 and later, not classes. The issue suggests that every constructor in a record with a primary constructor must call the primary constructor using this , otherwise the compiler wouldn't know how to handle the primary constructor parameters. I tried various approaches to resolve this issue, including creating a custom exception like TokenAcquisitionException and using this instead of base in the constructor. public class TokenAcquisitionException(string message) : Exception(message) { (10 more lines were trimmed) However, none of these approaches worked. Does anyone know how to correctly implement a constructor with an inner exception parameter in a C# class? Any help would be greatly appreciated. I was expecting that I could call the base class constructor with the same constructor signature: base(message, innerException) Typically, we can invoke the analogous constructor to pass responsibility for instantiation to the base class when the base class already significantly sets up the object.
